HEADWORD: Odeon
<hw>O*de"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, fr.
<?/: cf. F. <ets>od⟦eacute⟧on</ets>. See <er>Ode</er>.]</ety> <def>A
kind of theater in ancient Greece, smaller than the dramatic theater and
roofed over, in which poets and musicians submitted their works to the
approval of the public, and contended for prizes; -- hence, in modern
usage, the name of a hall for musical or dramatic
performances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

